'''Kashima Onata Shrine''' (かしまおなたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Miyagi Prefecture|Q47896|qid=Q47896|1=Miyagi Prefecture}} {{ill|lt=Watari District|Q1131765|qid=Q1131765|1=Watari District, Miyagi}} {{ill|lt=Watari|Q1205296|qid=Q1205296|1=Watari, Miyagi}}.
Its {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was village shrine. It is one of the four {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} for {{ill|lt=Watari District|Q1131765|qid=Q1131765|1=Watari District, Miyagi}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
; {{ill|qid=Q1502690|lt=Takemikazuchi|Q1502690|qid=Q1502690|qid=Q1502690|lt=Takemikazuchi|1=Takemikazuchi}}
: There is a theory that the name of Kashima Onata Shrine, like {{ill|lt=Kashima Amatarishiwake Shrine|Q11677110|qid=Q11677110|1=Kashima Amatarashi Wake Shrine}}, is derived from the name of Onata-no-kami, a child deity of Takemikazuchi.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, the shrine was established by imperial decree on the 6th day of the 8th month in the 41st year of {{ill|lt=Emperor Keikō|Q329723|qid=Q329723|1=Emperor Keikō}}'s reign. It is designated as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Engishiki|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, and in ancient times the entire Koyama district was shrine territory. Later, during the wars of the {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} era, the shrine lands fell into disuse. In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 (1872), the shrine was ranked as a {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=village shrine|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. Kashima Onata Shrine, together with {{ill|lt=Kashima Amatarishiwake Shrine|Q11677110|qid=Q11677110|1=Kashima Amatarashi Wake Shrine}}, is considered to be one of the two shrines enshrined in {{ill|lt=Watari District|Q1131765|qid=Q1131765|lt=Watari District|1=Watari District, Miyagi}} among the "thirty-eight shrines enshrining descendant deities of the great Kashima deity in Mutsu Province" recorded in the "{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}."

